        <div xml:id="AN17-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN17">
            <lg type="edition"><l>vaḷaṅkeḻu tirunakarp pantuciṟi teṟiyiṉu</l>
<l>miḷantuṇai yāyamoṭu kaḻaṅkuṭa ṉāṭiṉu</l>
<l>muyaṅkiṉ ṟaṉṉaiyeṉ meyyeṉ ṟacaii</l>
<l>mayaṅkiviyarp poṟitta nutala ṭaṇṇeṉa</l>
<l>muyaṅkiṉaḷ vatiyu muṉṉē <choice><seg><supplied>yi</supplied>ṉiyē</seg><seg>yiṉiya</seg></choice></l>
<l><choice><seg>toṭipāṇ</seg><seg>toṭimāṇ</seg></choice> cuṟṟamu memmu muḷḷā</l>
<l>ṇeṭumoḻit tantai yaruṅkaṭi nīvi</l>
<l>notuma lāḷa ṉeñcaṟap peṟṟaveṉ</l>
<l>ciṟumutuk kuṟaivi cilampār cīṟaṭi</l>
<l>vallakol cellat tāmē <choice><seg>kalleṉa</seg><seg>melleṉa</seg></choice></l>
<l>vūreḻun taṉṉa vurukeḻu celavi</l>
<l>ṉīri lattat tāriṭai maṭutta</l>
<l>koṭuṅkō lumaṇar pakaṭuteḻi teḷviḷi</l>
<l>neṭumperuṅ kuṉṟat timiḻkoḷa viyampuṅ</l>
<l>kaṭuṅkatir <choice><seg>tirukiya</seg><seg>murukiya</seg></choice> vēypayil piṟaṅkaṟ</l>
<l>peruṅkaḷi ṟuruñciya maṇṇarai yāat</l>
<l>taruñcurak kavalai yatarpaṭu maruṅki</l>
<l>ṉīḷarai yilavat <choice><seg>tūḻkaḻi</seg><seg>tūḻpaṭu</seg></choice> paṉmalar</l>
<l>viḻavuttalaik koṇṭa paḻaviṟaṉ mūtūr</l>
<l>neyyumiḻ cuṭariṟ kālporac cilki</l>
<l>vaikuṟu mīṉiṟ ṟōṉṟu</l>
<l><choice><seg>maipaṭu</seg><seg>meypaṭu</seg></choice> māmalai vilaṅkiya curaṉē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>In the prosperous, brilliant mansion, even when she threw the ball a little</l>
<l>and played with Molucca beans together with the companions, [her] young mates<note place="foot">The combination of tuṇai (used for couples either human or animal) and āyam (used for the group of girls surrounding HER) is unusual and it is not clear what kind of nuance is added with it.</note>,</l>
<l>she was wearied, saying “my body is tired, mother”,</l>
<l>her forehead diffusely marked with perspiration, she would stay</l>
<l>coolly in [my] embrace, formerly.</l>
<l rend="indent">	Now,</l>
<l>without thinking of [her] friends, [moving] with the tune of bangles, and of us,</l>
<l>brushing past the heavy protection of [her] father with long[-winded] speech,</l>
<l>will they have the strength to go,</l>
<l>the little feet noisy with anklets of my little [girl] lacking in ripeness</l>
<l>who has been gained, heart-stoppingly, by a strange man?</l>
<l>– through the desert where cloud-covered large mountains lie athwart,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where the clear whistles controlling the bulls of the saltmerchants with bent staffs</l>
<l rend="indent">	who unite for the difficult way on the waterless road</l>
<l rend="indent">	in fearful going, as if a [whole] village had risen, noisily,</l>
<l rend="indent">	sound so as to echo in the long big hills,</l>
<l rend="indent">	on sides where routes occur with crossroads through the difficult desert</l>
<l rend="indent">	of Yāam trees with earthy trunks on which the big elephant bull rubs itself,</l>
<l rend="indent">	glistening, rustling with bamboo wrung by the fierce beams,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where the very many whithered flowers of the long-trunked silk-cotton tree,</l>
<l rend="indent">	diminishing as the wind dashes at them, like the ghee-spitting lamps</l>
<l rend="indent">	of the old village with an ancient victory taken over by a festival,</l>
<l rend="indent">	appear like stars at dawn.</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
